(12, 32, 14, 'Snap is reportedly about to launch its own gaming platform', '<p><a class=\"crunchbase-link\" href=\"https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/snapchat/\" target=\"_blank\">Snap </a> is seeking to explore new ground as it tries to outrun Instagram&rsquo;s efforts to copy its features. Its newest effort may be building out a bona fide hub for gaming inside Snapchat, according to a new report from <a href=\"https://www.theinformation.com/articles/snap-gaming-platform-coming-this-fall\">The Information</a>. The platform will launch later this year, the report says, and Snap is already signing on game publishers to participate in its efforts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We reached out to Snap for comment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The news makes a lot of sense, given the efforts Snap has increasingly been pouring into its own Lens Studio software for developers to create its specialized AR filters. Snap reportedly bought a web-based 3D game engine last year, called <a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/2018/03/23/snap-reportedly-buys-its-own-3d-game-engine/\">PlayCanvas</a>, which would serve as a good backbone for even more robust developer tools.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s not clear from the report whether these gaming titles would be focused largely on AR gaming, though one might expect it given all of the attention Snap has paid to the emerging mobile platform.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In April, the company <a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/25/snappables-snapchat-games/\">launched</a> &ldquo;Snappables,&rdquo; which were basically short selfie AR games that integrate easily into Snapchat&rsquo;s Lens selection UI.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Augmented reality applications really benefit from sidling up closely to a camera platform, where you can snap a photo or record some video of an encounter with an AR T-Rex. This thinking benefits Snap. Snap is probably not competing with Google&rsquo;s ARCore or Apple&rsquo;s ARKit anymore; with these technologies, Snap simply seems to be striving to be the app that&rsquo;s home to several of these experiences. This is an advantage Snapchat still seems to hold over Facebook and Instagram&rsquo;s in-app cameras, which anecdotally don&rsquo;t seem to be used very heavily by users, though the companies have not released usage numbers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Snap won&rsquo;t exactly be blazing the trail with messaging-based gaming experiences. Facebook Messenger has already experimented with short, shareable mini-games. As noted by The Information report, CEO Evan Spiegel has expressed admiration for Tencent&rsquo;s business model, which sees nearly 40 percent of its revenues come from in-game purchases in the WeChat app. If the gaming platform did have a skew toward augmented reality, that would certainly be a unique proposition &mdash; though many of AR&rsquo;s promises have still been unrealized as developers grapple with what makes an engaging experience.</p>', 'snap-is-reportedly-about-to-launch-its-own-gaming-platform.jpeg', 0, 1, '2018-06-28 14:30:29', 'snap-is-reportedly-about-to-launch-its-own-gaming-platform', 'a:1:{s:9:\"published\";i:1;}'),
(13, 32, 7, 'Snap is reportedly about to launch its own gaming platform', '<p><a class=\"crunchbase-link\" href=\"https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/snapchat/\" target=\"_blank\">Snap </a> is seeking to explore new ground as it tries to outrun Instagram&rsquo;s efforts to copy its features. Its newest effort may be building out a bona fide hub for gaming inside Snapchat, according to a new report from <a href=\"https://www.theinformation.com/articles/snap-gaming-platform-coming-this-fall\">The Information</a>. The platform will launch later this year, the report says, and Snap is already signing on game publishers to participate in its efforts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We reached out to Snap for comment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The news makes a lot of sense, given the efforts Snap has increasingly been pouring into its own Lens Studio software for developers to create its specialized AR filters. Snap reportedly bought a web-based 3D game engine last year, called <a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/2018/03/23/snap-reportedly-buys-its-own-3d-game-engine/\">PlayCanvas</a>, which would serve as a good backbone for even more robust developer tools.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s not clear from the report whether these gaming titles would be focused largely on AR gaming, though one might expect it given all of the attention Snap has paid to the emerging mobile platform.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In April, the company <a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/25/snappables-snapchat-games/\">launched</a> &ldquo;Snappables,&rdquo; which were basically short selfie AR games that integrate easily into Snapchat&rsquo;s Lens selection UI.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Augmented reality applications really benefit from sidling up closely to a camera platform, where you can snap a photo or record some video of an encounter with an AR T-Rex. This thinking benefits Snap. Snap is probably not competing with Google&rsquo;s ARCore or Apple&rsquo;s ARKit anymore; with these technologies, Snap simply seems to be striving to be the app that&rsquo;s home to several of these experiences. This is an advantage Snapchat still seems to hold over Facebook and Instagram&rsquo;s in-app cameras, which anecdotally don&rsquo;t seem to be used very heavily by users, though the companies have not released usage numbers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Snap won&rsquo;t exactly be blazing the trail with messaging-based gaming experiences. Facebook Messenger has already experimented with short, shareable mini-games. As noted by The Information report, CEO Evan Spiegel has expressed admiration for Tencent&rsquo;s business model, which sees nearly 40 percent of its revenues come from in-game purchases in the WeChat app. If the gaming platform did have a skew toward augmented reality, that would certainly be a unique proposition &mdash; though many of AR&rsquo;s promises have still been unrealized as developers grapple with what makes an engaging experience.</p>', 'snap-is-reportedly-about-to-launch-its-own-gaming-platform.jpeg', 1, 0, '2018-06-28 16:03:15', 'snap-is-reportedly-about-to-launch-its-own-gaming-platform-1', 'a:1:{s:9:\"published\";i:1;}'),
(14, 32, 7, 'Yet another massive Facebook fail: Quiz app leaked data on ~120M users for years', '<p><a class=\"crunchbase-link\" href=\"https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/facebook/\" target=\"_blank\">Facebook </a> knows the historical app audit it&rsquo;s conducting in the wake of the Cambridge Analytica data misuse scandal is going to result in a tsunami of skeletons tumbling out of its closet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s already suspended around <a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/2018/05/14/facebook-suspends-200-suspicious-apps-out-of-thousands-reviewed-so-far/\">200 apps as a result of the audit</a>&nbsp;&mdash; which remains ongoing, with no formal timeline announced for when the process (and any associated investigations that flow from it) will be concluded.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>CEO&nbsp;<a class=\"crunchbase-link\" href=\"https://www.crunchbase.com/person/mark-zuckerberg/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">Mark Zuckerberg</a>&nbsp;announced the audit on&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/zuck/posts/10104712037900071\">March 21</a>, writing then that the company would &ldquo;investigate all apps that had access to large amounts of information before we changed our platform to dramatically reduce data access in 2014, and we will conduct a full audit of any app with suspicious activity&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But you do have to question how much the audit exercise is, first and foremost, intended to function as PR damage limitation for Facebook&rsquo;s brand &mdash; given the company&rsquo;s relaxed response to a data abuse report concerning a quiz app with ~120M monthly users, which it received right in the midst of the <a class=\"crunchbase-link\" href=\"https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/cambridge-analytica/\" target=\"_blank\">Cambridge Analytica </a> scandal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Because despite Facebook being alerted about the risk posed by the leaky quiz apps in late April &mdash; via its own data abuse bug bounty program &mdash; they were still live on its platform a month later.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It took about a further month for the vulnerability to be fixed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And, sure, Facebook was certainly busy over that period. Busy dealing with a major privacy scandal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Perhaps the company was putting rather more effort into&nbsp;<a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/10/how-facebook-has-reacted-since-the-data-misuse-scandal-broke/\">pumping out a steady stream of crisis PR</a>&nbsp;&mdash; including taking out <a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/2018/03/25/zuck-apologizes-for-cambridge-analytica-scandal-with-full-page-print-ad/\">full page newspaper adverts</a>&nbsp;(where it wrote that: &ldquo;we have a responsibility to protect your information. If we can&rsquo;t, we don&rsquo;t deserve it&rdquo;) &mdash; vs actually &lsquo;locking down the platform&rsquo;, per its repeat claims, even though the company&rsquo;s long and rich&nbsp;<a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/10/a-brief-history-of-facebooks-privacy-hostility-ahead-of-zuckerbergs-testimony/\">privacy-hostile history suggests otherwise</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Let&rsquo;s also not forget that, in early April, Facebook quietly&nbsp;<a href=\"https://newsroom.fb.com/news/2018/04/restricting-data-access/\">confessed to a major security flaw of its own</a> &mdash; when it admitted that an account search and recovery feature had been abused by &ldquo;malicious actors&rdquo; who, over what must have been a period of several years, had been able to surreptitiously collect personal data on a majority of Facebook&rsquo;s ~2BN users &mdash; and use that intel for whatever they fancied.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So Facebook users already have plenty reasons to doubt the company&rsquo;s claims to be able to &ldquo;protect your information&rdquo;.&nbsp;But this latest data fail facepalm suggests it&rsquo;s hardly scrambling to make amends for its own stinkingly bad legacy either.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Change will require regulation. And in <a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/tag/gdpr/\">Europe that has arrived</a>, in the form of the GDPR.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although it remains to be seen whether Facebook will face any data breach complaints in this specific instance, i.e. for not disclosing to affected users that their information was at risk of being exposed by the leaky quiz apps.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The regulation came into force on May 25 &mdash; and the javascript vulnerability was not fixed until June. So there may be grounds for concerned consumers to complain.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which Facebook data abuse victim am I?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Writing in a <a href=\"https://medium.com/@intideceukelaire/this-popular-facebook-app-publicly-exposed-your-data-for-years-12483418eff8\">Medium post</a>, the security researcher who filed the report &mdash; self-styled &ldquo;hacker&rdquo; Inti De Ceukelaire &mdash; explains he went hunting for data abusers on Facebook&rsquo;s platform after the company announced a <a href=\"https://newsroom.fb.com/news/2018/04/data-abuse-bounty/\">data abuse bounty</a> on April 10, as the company scrambled to present a responsible face to the world following revelations that a quiz app running on its platform had surreptitiously harvested millions of users&rsquo; data &mdash; data that had been passed to a controversial&nbsp;<a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/2018/05/02/cambridge-analytica-shuts-down/\">UK firm</a>&nbsp;which intended to use it to target political ads at US voters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>De Ceukelaire says he began his search by noting down what third party apps his Facebook friends were using &mdash; finding quizzes were one of the most popular apps. Plus he already knew quizzes had a reputation for being&nbsp;<a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/17/ca-also-used-sex-compass-and-other-quiz-apps-for-sucking-facebook-data-says-former-employee/\">data-suckers in a distracting wrapper</a>. So he took his first ever Facebook quiz, from a brand called NameTests.com, and quickly realized the company was exposing Facebook users&rsquo; data to &ldquo;any third-party that requested it&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The issue was that NameTests was displaying the quiz taker&rsquo;s personal data (such as full name, location, age, birthday) in a javascript file &mdash; thereby potentially exposing the identify and other data on logged in Facebook users to any external website they happened to visit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He also found it was providing an access token that allowed it to grant even more expansive data access permissions to third party websites &mdash; such as to users&rsquo; Facebook posts, photos and friends.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s not clear exactly why &mdash; but presumably relates to the quiz app company&rsquo;s own ad targeting activities. (Its&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.socialsweethearts.de/privacy_en.html\">privacy policy</a>&nbsp;states: &ldquo;We work together with various technological partners who, for example, display advertisements on the basis of user data. We make sure that the user&rsquo;s data is pseudonymised (e.g. no clear data such as names or e-mail addresses) and that users have simple rights of revocation at their disposal. We also conclude special data protection agreements with our partners, in which they commit themselves to the protection of user data.&rdquo; &mdash; which sounds great until you realize its javascript was just leaking people&rsquo;s personally identified data&hellip; [<em>facepalm</em>])</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Depending on what quizzes you took, the javascript could leak your facebook ID, first name, last name, language, gender, date of birth, profile picture, cover photo, currency, devices you use, when your information was last updated, your posts and statuses, your photos and your friends,&rdquo; writes De Ceukelaire.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He reckons people&rsquo;s data had been being publicly exposed since at least the end of 2016.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Facebook, NameTests describes its purpose thusly: &ldquo;Our goal is simple: To make people smile!&rdquo; &mdash; adding that its quizzes are intended as a bit of &ldquo;fun&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It doesn&rsquo;t shout so loudly that the &lsquo;price&rsquo; for taking one of its quizzes, say to find out what Disney princess you &lsquo;are&rsquo;, or what you could look like as an oil painting, is not only that it will suck out masses of your personal data (and potentially your friends&rsquo; data) from Facebook&rsquo;s platform for its own ad targeting purposes but was also, until recently, that your and other people&rsquo;s information could have been exposed to goodness&nbsp;knows who, for goodness knows what nefarious purposes&hellip;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Facebook-Cambridge Analytica data misuse scandal has underlined that ostensibly frivolous social data can end up being repurposed for all sorts of manipulative and power-grabbing purposes. (And not only can end up, but that quizzes are deliberately built to be data-harvesting tools&hellip; So think of that the next time you get a &lsquo;take this quiz&rsquo; notification asking &lsquo;what is in your fact file?&rsquo; or &lsquo;what has your date of birth imprinted on you&rsquo;? And hope ads is all you&rsquo;re being targeted for&hellip; )</p>\r\n\r\n<p>De Ceukelaire found that&nbsp;NameTests would still reveal Facebook users&rsquo; identity even after its app was deleted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;In order to prevent this from happening, the user would have had to manually delete the cookies on their device, since NameTests.com does not offer a log out functionality,&rdquo; he writes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I would imagine you wouldn&rsquo;t want any website to know who you are, let alone steal your information or photos. Abusing this flaw, advertisers could have targeted (political) ads based on your Facebook posts and friends. More explicit websites could have abused this flaw to blackmail their visitors, threatening to leak your sneaky search history to your friends,&rdquo; he adds, fleshing out the risks for affected Facebook users.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As well as alerting Facebook to the vulnerability, De Ceukelaire says he contacted NameTests &mdash; and they claimed to have found no evidence of abuse by a third party. They also said they would make changes to fix the issue.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&rsquo;ve reached out to NameTests&rsquo; parent company &mdash; a German firm called Social Sweethearts &mdash; for comment. Its&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.socialsweethearts.de/en_US/#portfolio\">website</a> touts a &ldquo;data-driven approach&rdquo; &mdash; and claims its portfolio of products achieve &ldquo;a global organic reach of several billion page views per month&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After De Ceukelaire reported the problem to Facebook, he says he received an&nbsp;initial response from the company on April 30 saying they were looking into it. Then, hearing nothing for some weeks, he sent a follow up email, on May 14, asking whether they had contacted the app developers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A week later Facebook replied saying&nbsp;it could take three to six months to investigate the issue (i.e. the same timeframe mentioned in their initial automated reply), adding they would keep him in the loop.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yet at that time &mdash; which was a month after his original report &mdash; the leaky NameTests quizzes were still up and running,&nbsp; meaning Facebook users&rsquo; data was still being exposed and at risk. And Facebook knew about the risk.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The next development came on June 25, when De Ceukelaire says he noticed NameTests had changed the way they process data to close down the access they had been exposing to third parties.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Two days later Facebook also confirmed the flaw in writing, admitting: &ldquo;[T]his could have allowed an attacker to determine the details of a logged-in user to Facebook&rsquo;s platform.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It also told him it had confirmed with NameTests the issue had been fixed. And its&nbsp;apps continue to be available on Facebook&rsquo;s platform &mdash; suggesting Facebook did not find the kind of suspicious activity that has led it to suspend other third party apps. (At least, assuming it conducted an investigation.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Facebook paid out a $4,000 x2 bounty to a charity under the terms of its data abuse bug bounty program &mdash; and per De Ceukelaire&rsquo;s request.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We asked it what took it so long to respond to&nbsp;the data abuse report, especially given the issue was so topical when De Ceukelaire filed the report. But Facebook declined to answer specific questions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead it sent us the following statement, attributed to Ime Archibong, its VP of product partnerships:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A researcher brought the issue with the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://nametests.com/\">nametests.com</a>&nbsp;website to our attention through our Data Abuse Bounty Program that we launched in April to encourage reports involving Facebook data. We worked with&nbsp;<a href=\"http://nametests.com/\">nametests.com</a>&nbsp;to resolve the vulnerability on their website, which was completed in June.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Facebook also claims it received&nbsp;De Ceukelaire&rsquo;s report on&nbsp;April 27, rather than April 22, as he recounts it. Though it&rsquo;s possible the former date is when Facebook&rsquo;s own staff retrieved the report from its systems.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Beyond displaying a disturbingly relaxed attitude to other people&rsquo;s privacy &mdash; which risks getting Facebook into regulatory trouble, given GDPR&rsquo;s strict requirements around breach disclosure, for example &mdash; the other core issue of concern here is the company&rsquo;s apparent failure to enforce its own developer policy.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The underlying issue is whether or not Facebook performs any checks on apps running on its platform. It&rsquo;s no good having T&amp;Cs if you don&rsquo;t have any active processes to enforce your T&amp;Cs. Rules without enforcement aren&rsquo;t worth the paper they&rsquo;re written on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Historical evidence suggests Facebook did not actively enforce its developer T&amp;Cs &mdash; even if it&rsquo;s now &ldquo;locking down the platform&rdquo;, as it claims, as a result of so many privacy scandals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The quiz app developer at the center of the Cambridge Analytica scandal, Aleksandr Kogan &mdash; who harvested and sold/passed Facebook user data to third parties &mdash; has&nbsp;<a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/24/kogan-i-dont-think-facebook-has-a-developer-policy-that-is-valid/\">accused Facebook of essentially not having a policy</a>.&nbsp;He contends it is therefore Facebook who is responsible for the massive data abuses that have played out on its platform &mdash; only a portion of which have so far come to light.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fresh examples such as NameTests&rsquo; leaky quiz apps merely bolster the case Kogan made for Facebook being the guilty party where data misuse is concerned. After all,&nbsp;if you built some stables without any doors at all would you really blame your horses for bolting?</p>', 'yet-another-massive-facebook-fail-quiz-app-leaked-data-on-120m-users-for-years.jpeg', 0, 1, '2018-06-28 17:18:30', 'yet-another-massive-facebook-fail-quiz-app-leaked-data-on-120m-users-for-years', 'a:1:{s:9:\"published\";i:1;}'),
(15, 32, 1, 'Yoobic raises $25M for an app that helps retailers track in-store merchandising campaigns', '<p>A lot of the innovation we&rsquo;ve seen in the world of commerce has been focused on the front end of the business: how to use digital tools to improve shoppers&rsquo; experiences both online and offline &mdash; ultimately get them to buy more. Today, however, comes news of some funding for a startup that has built an app to help the retailers themselves. Yoobic, whose SaaS platform lets retail staff communicate with head offices to plan and execute merchandising and marketing campaigns using technology like computer vision to get the job done &mdash; to make the in-store experience as agile as the online one, in the words of CEO and co-founder</p>\r\n\r\n<p>has raised $25 million in funding, money that it will use to expand beyond its home markets of London and Europe to the US.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The funding is being led by Insight Venture Partners, the prolific investor that has been especially active of late. Felix Capital, which led the startup&rsquo;s Series A, is also in this round.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The money comes on the heels of strong growth for Yoobic: revenues are up by 143 percent between 2016 and 2017, and the product is now being used by 100 retailers and their wider range of 20,000 stores in 44 countries. Some 100,000 tasks get completed each month using the app each month, a 250 percent rise versus 2017. Customers include a number of luxury brands, Lacoste, the Casino Group, Aldi UK (part of Aldi Sud, which also has operations in the US; Aldi Nord, a separate business, owns Trader Joe&rsquo;s), and car companies like Peugeot and Citroen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yoobic is using the power of technology to address a particular pain point in the world of retail. When a company &mdash; either a brand or the retailer selling goods &mdash; has merchandise dispersed across multiple locations, it becomes a challenge to sell items in a consistent way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A sale, or a particular campaign, or simply just a house style for how to lay out products are all scenarios that are hard to do consistently and efficiently when you have a disparate staff of salespeople &mdash; the average level of churn of retail salespeople is 50 percent annually and it&rsquo;s rising &mdash;&nbsp;needing to take communications from a central office and people who may be nowhere in your physical vicinity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yoobic&rsquo;s solution is a platform that works on a mobile app &mdash; or a computer, although the vast majority of salespeople use mobile devices as they do not sit at desks &mdash; that provides running conversations around different campaigns, with instructions of how to present items.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Crucially, it&rsquo;s very simple to use: you need something simple not just because of employee churn, but because campaigns, sales and other changes in retail layout potentially might be taking place throughout the day, said&nbsp;Fabrice Ha&iuml;at, CEO and co-founder of Yoobic. &ldquo;We don&rsquo;t have time to train.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The remote salespeople can use their device&rsquo;s camera to shoot their own layouts to check them against the provided instructions, and the app&rsquo;s algorithms checks these automatically and suggests changes where they might be needed. When everything meets specifications, notifications get sent to managers at the head office to let them know that the layout has been completed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Down the line, the same systems can potentially be used for inventory checks, updates on in-store footfall, and other physical details that are harder to monitor when you&rsquo;re not at the store. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re just scratching the surface,&rdquo; Ha&iuml;at said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ha&iuml;at added that in the past, a company would have had to rely on managers&rsquo; assessments, or in-store checks to monitor whether things are running as they should be, but that can be inconsistent, or costly if you do it well. Similarly, messaging has always been slow and clumsy. &ldquo;The communications between a store and head office have been based around emails,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;The object is to kill the email and replace it with an intelligent task management solution.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The rise of Yoobic &mdash; which actually <a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/video/yoobic-keeps-the-in-store-experience-great/\">made its debut on TechCrunch&rsquo;s Disrupt stage</a>&nbsp;&mdash; mirrors that of how the retail industry has tried to tap into the advances of technology to make their operations more efficient, and more profitable, not just to improve the experience but to make sure that brick-and-mortar can keep pace with whatever advantages online sales, and online sales behemoths like Amazon, might have.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It may be some time before physical commerce becomes devoid of all human involvement &mdash; an endgame that companies like <a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/2018/01/21/inside-amazons-surveillance-powered-no-checkout-convenience-store/\">Amazon are already testing</a> &mdash; but in the meantime, we&rsquo;re seeing innovations like&nbsp;better experiences in trying to figure out what might look good on you, how to find what you want in a store, more efficient check-out flows, and stronger links between purchasing&nbsp;and how users are browsing online. All of those are now being digitised and that&rsquo;s creating a vast array of data points that map out a customer&rsquo;s digital profile.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While Yoobic doesn&rsquo;t directly tie in with the customer experience, the work that it enables definitely makes use of those data points, and contributes to fulfilling bigger marketing strategies. &ldquo;For example, say you get data from the point-of-sale system that indicates that sales of Coke are dropping, but you also know you&rsquo;re about to have a heatwave,&rdquo; Ha&iuml;at explained. &ldquo;A retailer can use Yoobic to lay out a promotional display for Coke to meet that potential demand and boost sales of the drink in the process.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yoobic also offers an API that can integrate the service into other systems &mdash; there are already integrations with Workplace and Slack,&nbsp;Ha&iuml;at said, which mean Yoobic itself isn&rsquo;t used for basic messaging and chat services, just the business of retailing, marketing and selling.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;The YOOBIC team has created a best-in-class product offering and we are looking forward to working on the company&rsquo;s future and expansion in the US,&rdquo; said&nbsp;Jeff Lieberman, MD of Insight Venture Partners, in a statement. &ldquo;We believe solutions like this will become a must-have for retailers, and that YOOBIC has the opportunity and the potential to become the leader of its category.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Interestingly, the founders of Yoobic &mdash; Fabrice, Avi, and Gilles Ha&iuml;at, all brothers &mdash; are serial entrepreneurs whose previous startup, Vizelia, was <a href=\"http://www2.schneider-electric.com/corporate/en/press/press-releases/viewer-press-releases.page?c_filepath=/templatedata/Content/Financial_Release/data/en/shared/2010/12/20101209_schneider_electric_strengthens_its_position_in_complete_solutions_for_.xml\">sold to Schneider Electric</a>. It had an interesting parallel to what they have built with Yoobic: it was a energy monitoring solution for buildings. &ldquo;Initially we were monitoring energy, and now we are monitoring retail,&rdquo; Fabrice said. &ldquo;Conceptually, there is a connection.&rdquo;</p>', 'yoobic-raises-25m-for-an-app-that-helps-retailers-track-in-store-merchandising-campaigns.jpeg', 1, 1, '2018-06-29 13:16:05', 'yoobic-raises-25m-for-an-app-that-helps-retailers-track-in-store-merchandising-campaigns', 'a:1:{s:9:\"published\";i:1;}'),
(19, 32, 14, 'A closer look at Google Duplex', '<p>A month and change after<a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/2018/05/08/8-big-announcements-from-google-i-o-2018/\"> I/O,</a> <a class=\"crunchbase-link\" href=\"https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/google/\" target=\"_blank\">Google </a> convenes a meeting of a few small groups of journalists at an upscale Thai restaurant in Manhattan&rsquo;s Upper East Side. It&rsquo;s an unusual locale for one of the world&rsquo;s largest companies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The tables are cleared out to make room for nine chairs, in three rows of three, facing a large, brightly lit display. To the side, four Google employees sit behind a desk at a makeshift control center. The company is finally ready to offer a little more insight into <a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/2018/05/08/the-google-assistant-will-soon-be-able-to-call-restaurants-and-make-a-reservations-for-you/\">Duplex</a>, the most widely discussed &mdash; and <a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/2018/05/10/duplex-shows-google-failing-at-ethical-and-creative-ai-design/\">controversial</a> announcement during a rapid-fire keynote.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s a 180-degree shift from that sun-drenched day at Mountain View&rsquo;s Shoreline Ampitheatre. All by design, of course. The cozy New York restaurant makes as much sense as any for such an event, as the company pulls back the curtain on the AI-based reservation service. Thep Thai&rsquo;s owner insists that such a service would be something of a godsend for the 100-plus reservations the restaurant fields on a daily basis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For Google, it was clearly time to offer some more transparency into both the purpose for such a system and the workings behind it. The brief demo presented by CEO Sundar Pichai raised far more questions than it answered. The think pieces began to flow, exploring the ethical ramifications for a system that appeared to be designed to fool a business into believing they were talking to a fellow human being.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Duplex represents a rare early look into an ongoing project from a company notorious for playing it close to the vest. But disclosure is key. As with self-driving cars, rigorous real-world testing is required to iron out all of the kinks in the system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;While we&rsquo;re not widely launching this feature yet, we&rsquo;re sharing more information about this technology to provide transparency and encourage feedback,&rdquo; the company writes in a blog post today. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s important that we get the experience right both for people and for businesses, and we&rsquo;re taking a slow and measured approach as we incorporate learnings and feedback from our tests.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The nature of Google&rsquo;s process was likely to get out some way or another, so announcing it at I/O served the dual purpose of getting in front of that narrative and offering an early look at an ambitious project on one of the company&rsquo;s largest stages.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;What you&rsquo;re going to hear is the Google Assistant scheduling an appointment at a real hair salon,&rdquo; Pichai said to tentative applause during the keynote:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hi, I&rsquo;m calling to book a women&rsquo;s haircut for a client. Um, I&rsquo;m looking for something on May 3. &ndash; Google Assistant</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sure, give me one second. &ndash; Receptionist</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mm-hm. &ndash; Google Assistant</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was here the audience laughed, unbelieving. Then applause. Sure, the audience was in on the joke, but it was still hard to believe that what we were hearing was a purely automated version of Google&rsquo;s AI assistant. The &ldquo;mm-hm&rdquo; was icing on the cake &mdash; a subtle vocal tick included to further conversation, all while leaving the other party none the wiser that she was speaking to a &lsquo;bot.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Those vocal breaks, known as &ldquo;speech disfluencies&rdquo; in linguistics, are a normal and frequent part of speech, and a key part of the secret sauce that makes Duplex such a remarkable product. Among other things, they&rsquo;re a polite workaround for the system.</p>', 'a-closer-look-at-google-duplex.jpeg', 1, 1, '2018-07-03 10:03:24', 'a-closer-look-at-google-duplex', 'a:1:{s:9:\"published\";i:1;}');
INSERT INTO `article` (`id`, `category_id`, `author_id`, `title`, `content`, `featured_image`, `special`, `spotlight`, `created_at`, `slug`, `status`) VALUES
(20, 32, 14, 'Coupe du monde 2018 : des buts, du talent, du génie... Le Mondial à toute vitesse de Kylian Mbappé', '<p><em>Le num&eacute;ro 10 des Bleus, buteur en finale contre la Croatie, a &eacute;t&eacute; la grande star de l&#39;&eacute;quipe de France. &Agrave; 19 ans, le pr&eacute;sent et l&#39;avenir lui appartiennent. </em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>&quot;J&#39;avais 20 ans et je ne laisserai personne dire que c&#39;est le plus bel &acirc;ge de la vie.&quot;</em>&nbsp;On ne sait pas si Kylian Mbapp&eacute; a&nbsp;lu <em>Aden Arabie</em> de&nbsp;Paul Nizan, rest&eacute; c&eacute;l&egrave;bre pour son incipit. Le joueur du PSG n&#39;a pas encore 20 ans, et tout lui sourit. &Agrave; 19 ans et 6 mois,&nbsp;il est champion du monde apr&egrave;s <a href=\"https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sports/foot/coupe-du-monde/finale-france-croatie/coupe-du-monde-2018-le-bijou-de-mbappe-la-boulette-de-lloris-le-retour-de-la-var-ce-qu-il-faut-retenir-de-la-finale-remportee-par-les-bleus-face-a-la-croatie_2851745.html\" target=\"_blank\">la victoire des Bleus contre la Croatie (4-2)</a>,&nbsp;a marqu&eacute; en finale et talonne d&eacute;sormais la l&eacute;gende br&eacute;silienne Pel&eacute; dans les statistiques. Le joueur du PSG&nbsp;termine sa premi&egrave;re <a href=\"https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sports/foot/coupe-du-monde/\" target=\"_blank\">Coupe du monde</a> qu&#39;il a travers&eacute;e comme dans un r&ecirc;ve.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>19 - Kylian Mbapp&eacute; est le 2e plus jeune joueur &agrave; marquer en finale de Coupe du Monde (19 ans &amp; 6 mois) apr&egrave;s Pel&eacute; face &agrave; la Su&egrave;de en 1958 (17 ans &amp; 8 mois). Extraterrestre. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/hashtag/FRACRO?src=hash&amp;ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw\">#FRACRO</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/hashtag/CM2018?src=hash&amp;ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw\">#CM2018</a> <a href=\"https://t.co/FnjWuJKcC9\">pic.twitter.com/FnjWuJKcC9</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&mdash; OptaJean (@OptaJean) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/OptaJean/status/1018533182130524164?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw\">15 juillet 2018</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&Eacute;lu meilleur jeune de la comp&eacute;tition</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Depuis son &eacute;closion supersonique &agrave; l&#39;AS Monaco et son transfert record au PSG l&#39;&eacute;t&eacute; dernier, la question n&#39;&eacute;tait&nbsp;pas de savoir si Kylian Mbapp&eacute; peut &ecirc;tre titulaire lors de la Coupe du monde en Russie, mais plut&ocirc;t &agrave; quel poste. Avant-centre ou alors sur un c&ocirc;t&eacute; ? Didier Deschamps a tr&egrave;s vite tranch&eacute; en l&#39;alignant sur l&#39;aile droite o&ugrave; sa vitesse et son sens du but auront fait merveille et rendu de grands services aux Bleus durant un mois.&nbsp;En finale, s&#39;il n&#39;a pas survol&eacute; la rencontre, il a encore lib&eacute;r&eacute; l&#39;&eacute;quipe de France en marquant d&#39;une frappe &agrave; l&#39;entr&eacute;e de la surface. Un but o&ugrave; il a fait admirer sa souplesse et son intelligence. Sa gestuelle et son langage corporel laissaient penser &agrave; une frappe enroul&eacute;e. Il va finalement surpendre le d&eacute;fenseur et le portier croates en frappant s&egrave;chement au premier poteau. Sa quatri&egrave;me r&eacute;alisation de la comp&eacute;tition &ndash; il termine co-meilleur buteur fran&ccedil;ais avec Antoine Griezmann (4 buts).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&Agrave; 19 ans, il succ&egrave;de &agrave; son co&eacute;quipier Paul Pogba sacr&eacute; en 2014 au Br&eacute;sil en &eacute;tant sacr&eacute; meilleur jeune de la comp&eacute;tition.&nbsp;La&nbsp;pression de cet &eacute;v&eacute;nement plan&eacute;taire a sembl&eacute; glisser sur lui. Il a promen&eacute; son talent et son insouciance sur les pelouses de Russie. Mais, pour la premi&egrave;re fois depuis un mois, lors de cette finale, il a sembl&eacute; rattrap&eacute; par l&#39;&eacute;v&egrave;nement. <em>&quot;Il&nbsp;a couru vite, c&rsquo;est vrai, comme d&rsquo;habitude. Il a marqu&eacute;, encore. Mais sinon, je trouve qu&rsquo;il a &eacute;t&eacute; un peu d&eacute;cevant, parfois brouillon. On peut aussi mettre cela sur le compte du stress, de la pression. Il a 19 ans&quot;</em>, remarque Thibaud Leplat, l&#39;auteur du livre <em>Football &agrave; la fran&ccedil;aise,</em> joint par franceinfo.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Des records de pr&eacute;cocit&eacute; &agrave; la pelle</p>\r\n\r\n<p>L&#39;&acirc;ge, un argument qu&#39;il n&#39;a jamais accept&eacute;, comme il l&#39;&eacute;voquait lors de l&#39;&eacute;mission&nbsp; de Canal+, <em>Int&eacute;rieur Sport</em>, qui lui &eacute;tait consacr&eacute;e.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Il n&#39;y a pas de &#39;t&#39;as l&#39;&acirc;ge ou tu n&#39;as pas l&#39;&acirc;ge&#39;. Si tu es bon, tu es sur le terrain, tu assumes. Si tu n&#39;es pas bon, tu te tais, tu es sur le banc, tu regardes les autres (...) Moi, tu ne me parles pas d&#39;&acirc;ge.Kylian Mbapp&eacute;, joueur de l&#39;&eacute;quipe de France&agrave; Int&eacute;rieur Sport</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Surnomm&eacute; &quot;Razmoket&quot; par ses co&eacute;quipiers en s&eacute;lection, Mbapp&eacute; a donn&eacute; raison &agrave; l&#39;adage qui veut que le talent&nbsp;n&#39;attend pas le nombre d&#39;ann&eacute;es. Durant un mois, le natif de Bondy (Seine-Saint-Denis) aura pass&eacute; son temps &agrave; effacer des tablettes des records de pr&eacute;cocit&eacute;. Discret face &agrave; l&#39;Australie, il devient pourtant le plus jeune joueur tricolore &agrave; disputer une rencontre d&#39;un tournoi majeur (Euro, Coupe du monde). Face au P&eacute;rou, il enl&egrave;ve une belle &eacute;pine du pied aux Bleus en marquant le seul but de la rencontre. En poussant dans le but vide la frappe d&#39;Olivier Giroud, et devient donc le plus jeune buteur des Bleus en tournois majeurs. Mis au repos par Didier Deschamps pour la rencontre &quot;pour du beurre&quot; face au Danemark, Kylian Mbapp&eacute; reserve le meilleur pour les matchs &agrave; &eacute;limination directe... et montrer le meilleur.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>En huiti&egrave;mes de finale, il d&eacute;fie l&#39;Argentine de Lionel Messi. Et il va sortir largement vainqueur de son duel &agrave; distance avec la star du FC Barcelone. Ses acc&eacute;l&eacute;rations&nbsp;ont mis&nbsp;au supplice une arri&egrave;re-garde compl&egrave;tement d&eacute;pass&eacute;e. Il provoque un penalty apr&egrave;s une course folle,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sports/foot/coupe-du-monde/video-usain-bolt-un-elephant-un-coq-qui-court-plus-vite-que-kylian-mbappe_2832317.html\" target=\"_blank\">o&ugrave; il est flash&eacute; &agrave; 37 km/h</a>&nbsp;(officialis&eacute; &agrave; 32). Il s&#39;offre ensuite un doubl&eacute; : un but de renard et une frappe crois&eacute;e apr&egrave;s une folle chevauch&eacute;e. Il devient le deuxi&egrave;me plus jeune joueur &agrave; mettre un doubl&eacute; en Coupe du monde apr&egrave;s Pel&eacute; en 1958. La presse du monde entier est &agrave; ses pieds, rapporte <em><a href=\"https://www.francefootball.fr/news/Phenomene-mbappe-il-a-relegue-messi-au-second-plan-talent-infini-la-presse-mondiale-aux-pieds-de-kylian-mbappe/922293\" target=\"_blank\">France Football</a>.&nbsp;</em>D&eacute;j&agrave; surveill&eacute; par les d&eacute;fenses adverses, il devient alors le danger num&eacute;ro un d&#39;une attaque o&ugrave;, quand Griezmann et Giroud font les efforts pour le collectif, lui appuie sur l&#39;acc&eacute;l&eacute;rateur. Pied au plancher.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Le feu d&#39;artifice de la finale</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>&quot;Malgr&eacute; son jeune &acirc;ge, il d&eacute;montre &eacute;norm&eacute;ment de qualit&eacute;s. Il d&eacute;gage beaucoup de force, et c&rsquo;est vrai que c&rsquo;est un danger permanent pour l&rsquo;adversaire&quot;</em>, s&#39;enthousiasmait Blaise Matuidi en conf&eacute;rence de presse. L&#39;Uruguay et la Belgique ont conscience de la menace Mbappe et vont le marquer de pr&egrave;s. L&#39;Uruguayen Cristian Rodriguez lui chatouillera m&ecirc;me les c&ocirc;tes d&#39;un peu trop pr&egrave;s, lui faisant payer une fantaisie, une passe en talonnade, alors que la France menait 2-0. Le carton jaune r&eacute;colt&eacute; lui fait perdre ses nerfs ce qui lui vaudra une belle soufflante de Didier Deschamps. <em>&quot;Kylian, OH&nbsp;! &Eacute;coute-moi... Arr&ecirc;te de faire chier, stop et c&#39;est tout. Tu ne le m&eacute;rites pas (le carton jaune), mais ne fais pas &ccedil;a&nbsp;!&nbsp;Allez, l&acirc;che rien&quot;</em>, lui a lanc&eacute; son s&eacute;lectionneur depuis le banc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Kylian...Kyyylllliiiaaaannnn&quot;<br />\r\nDidier Deschamps revient dans <a href=\"https://twitter.com/telefoot_TF1?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw\">@telefoot_TF1</a> sur ses mots pour <a href=\"https://twitter.com/KMbappe?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw\">@KMbappe</a> pendant France - Uruguay. Regardez ⤵⤵<a href=\"https://t.co/YnfEpGct1U\">https://t.co/YnfEpGct1U</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&mdash; T&eacute;l&eacute;foot (@telefoot_TF1) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/telefoot_TF1/status/1015905048323338246?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw\">8 juillet 2018</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Muet face &agrave; la Celeste en quarts de finale, il ne fait pas trembler les filets non plus contre les Belges en demie. Mais face aux Diables rouges, il fait admirer son art de la provocation balle aux pieds avec 15 dribbles tent&eacute;s (7 r&eacute;ussis). En finale, il a souvent souffert face au marquage serr&eacute; d&#39;Ivan Strinic. Mais il a r&eacute;ussi &agrave; sortir de sa bo&icirc;te en seconde p&eacute;riode, l&agrave; o&ugrave; les espaces, qu&#39;il aime tant avaler, se sont cr&eacute;&eacute;s. Apr&egrave;s la rencontre au micro de TF1, il a affich&eacute; sa maturit&eacute; habituelle&nbsp;: <em>&quot;</em><em>Je suis tr&egrave;s content. J&#39;avais affich&eacute; mes ambitions collectives au d&eacute;but du Mondial. La route a &eacute;t&eacute; longue mais cela valait le coup. On est fiers de rendre les Fran&ccedil;ais heureux&quot;</em>, a-t-il d&#39;abord d&eacute;clar&eacute;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Je ne veux pas simplement &ecirc;tre de passage dans le foot&nbsp;: &ecirc;tre champion du monde, c&#39;est un message. Je veux faire encore mieux, mais champion du monde, c&#39;est d&eacute;j&agrave; bien.Kylian Mbapp&eacute;, joueur de l&#39;&eacute;quipe de France&agrave; TF1</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Champion du monde &agrave; 19 ans, il a tout l&#39;avenir devant lui&nbsp;et ne compte pas s&#39;arr&ecirc;ter en si bon chemin. Il&nbsp;va falloir s&#39;accrocher pour r&eacute;ussir &agrave; le suivre.</p>', 'coupe-du-monde-2018-des-buts-du-talent-du-genie-le-mondial-a-toute-vitesse-de-kylian-mbappe.jpeg', 0, 1, '2018-07-16 12:57:24', 'coupe-du-monde-2018-des-buts-du-talent-du-genie-le-mondial-a-toute-vitesse-de-kylian-mbappe', 'a:1:{s:9:\"published\";i:1;}');

